# Simple Platformer


## Welcome @showdialog

Welcome to **Jungle Monkey Jump!**

Here, you'll learn how to make a [__*sidescrolling*__](#scrolld "games that are viewed from the side, with most of the action happening horizontally") 
[__*platformer*__](#plat "games that rely on jump and run as their main mechanic").  

![Our first platformer](/static/skillmap/jungle/jungle1.gif "Look what we're about to learn today!")

This kind of game peeks in on the action from the side, and relies on a [__*tilemap*__](#tiled "a scene or world created using predefined tiles")  for placement of the main goals, decorations, and obstacles.




## Step 2 

**Your scene has already been set!**

---

‚ñ∫ Look at your workspace to see that the background image and tilemap have already been set for the scene in this activity.  

üí° Both blocks have been added to the ``||loops: on start||`` container, so that they load as soon as the game starts.



## Step 3 - We need a HERO

**üêí We need a hero üêí**

Our moving characters are called [__*sprites*__](#sprote "2-D images that move on the screen"). Let's create a main sprite and get it moving before we do anything else. 

---

‚ñ∫ From the ``||sprites:Sprites||`` category, drag ``||variables:set [mySprite] to sprite [ ] of kind [Player]||`` to **the end** of the ``||loops:on start||`` container.

‚ñ∫ To choose a standing monkey, click the empty grey box, then toggle to **My Assets** and click the monkey named **stand**.


```blocks
scene.setBackgroundImage(assets.image`background`)
tiles.setTilemap(tilemap`level1`)
// @highlight
let mySprite = sprites.create(assets.image`Stand`, SpriteKind.Player)
```


## Step 4 - Control the Player

**‚ÜîÔ∏è Time to get the player moving ‚ÜîÔ∏è**

---

‚ñ∫ From ``||controller:Controller||``, drag ``||controller:move [mySprite] with buttons ‚äï||``   
to **the end** of the ``||loops:on start||`` container.

‚ñ∫ Press the ‚äï button to the right of the block and change the [__*vy*__](#whatVY "vertical velocity") 
argument to **0** so that the player won't hover up or down with the joypad.  


```blocks
scene.setBackgroundImage(assets.image`background`)
tiles.setTilemap(tilemap`level1`)
let mySprite = sprites.create(assets.image`Stand`, SpriteKind.Player)
// @highlight
controller.moveSprite(mySprite, 100, 0)
```


## Step 5 - Try It

**üïπÔ∏è Be sure to give your game a try on the game screen üïπÔ∏è **

---

How do you like it?  Feel like making a few more changes?


## Step 6 - Add gravity

**To make the game feel more realistic, it needs gravity.**

For that, add [__*acceleration*__](#accel "increased speed in a direction")
to "pull down" on the sprite.

---

‚ñ∫  From ``||sprites:Sprites||``, drag ``||sprites:set [mySprite] [x] to [0]||`` to **the end** of the ``||loops:on start||`` container.

‚ñ∫ Click the dropdown to change **x** to **ay (acceleration y)** 

‚ñ∫ Replace **0** with **500** to send the sprite falling toward the ground.

```blocks
scene.setBackgroundImage(assets.image`background`)
tiles.setTilemap(tilemap`level1`)
let mySprite = sprites.create(assets.image`Stand`, SpriteKind.Player)
controller.moveSprite(mySprite, 100, 0)
// @highlight
mySprite.ay = 500
```

## Step 7 - Follow with Camera

**Oops!  The monkey falls off-screen!**

---

‚ñ∫  To keep the monkey in sight, open ``||scene:Scene||`` and drag 
``||scene:camera follow sprite [mySprite]||`` to **the end** of the ``||loops:on start||`` container.

```blocks
scene.setBackgroundImage(assets.image`background`)
tiles.setTilemap(tilemap`level1`)
let mySprite = sprites.create(assets.image`Stand`, SpriteKind.Player)
controller.moveSprite(mySprite, 100, 0)
mySprite.ay = 500
// @highlight
scene.cameraFollowSprite(mySprite)

```


## Step 8 - Look Again

**üïπÔ∏è Try your game again and make sure the monkey lands üïπÔ∏è **



## Step 9 - Jump

Now that the monkey has safely landed, we can make it jump when we press the **up** arrow!

---

‚ñ∫ From ``||controller:Controller||``, drag the ``||controller:on [A] button [pressed]||`` container into an empty area of the workspace.

‚ñ∫ Click the **A** option and change it to **up**.

‚ñ∫ Inside of the ``||controller:on [up] button [pressed]||`` container, add ``||sprites:make [mySprite] gravity jump||``. 

```blocks
controller.up.onEvent(ControllerButtonEvent.Pressed, function () {
    let mySprite: Sprite = null
    gravity_jump(mySprite)
})
```

üî• **That's it! Now give your game a try!** üî•

```customts
namespace sprites {
    //% block="make $thisSprite=variables_get(mySprite) gravity jump"
    export function gravity_jump (thisSprite: Sprite) {
    if (thisSprite.isHittingTile(CollisionDirection.Bottom)) {
        thisSprite.vy = -200
    }
}
}
```
